    {
      "question": "Two street light contractors, Company A and Company B, install lights on a straight road. Company A installs a light every $36$ meters and Company B installs a light every $48$ meters. If they both install a light at the starting point (position $0$ meters), at what distance from the start will they next install a light at the same position? If the road is $1$ kilometer long, how many times will their lights coincide (excluding the start)?",
      "answer": "First coincidence at $144$ meters; $6$ coincidences in $1$ kilometer.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "To find the first point of coincidence, calculate the LCM of $36$ and $48$.",
          "Prime factorisation of $36 = 2^2 \\times 3^2$.",
          "Prime factorisation of $48 = 2^4 \\times 3^1$.",
          "$LCM(36, 48) = 2^4 \\times 3^2 = 16 \\times 9 = 144$.",
          "The lights coincide every $144$ meters.",
          "Total length of road is $1000$ meters.",
          "Number of coincidences $= \\lfloor 1000 \\div 144 \\rfloor = \\lfloor 6.94 \\rfloor = 6$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$36 = 2^2 \\times 3^2 \\\\ 48 = 2^4 \\times 3 \\\\ LCM = 2^4 \\times 3^2 = 144 \\\\ 1000 \\div 144 = 6.944... \\\\ \\text{Number of coincidences} = 6$"
      },
